The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Tuesday, August 03, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		Calcutta Municipal Corporation (CMC) had a record low earning on Monday due to the 12-hour Bengal bandh. According to civic officials, the CMC notched up less than Rs 1 lakh, against an average daily earning of Rs 1.1 crore. Officials said very few people came to the civic headquarters to deposit taxes. Attendance at the Trinamul Congress-run civic address was also poor, pegged at around 30 per cent. At Bidhannagar Municipality, however, attendance was high. Sutanu Kar, sub-divisional officer, Salt Lake, said there was 70 per cent attendance at the townships civic body, in defiance of the Trinamul shutdown.																																																		Gopal Jana, 52, a resident of south Calcutta, hanged himself on Monday for being unable to admit his son to college for financial reasons. Jana, who hanged himself from the bedroom ceiling of his Diamond Harbour Road home on Monday afternoon, wrote in his suicide note that he was taking the step as he was he could not support his son Biswajits higher education. Biswajit passed this years Higher Secondary examination. 																																																		Eastern Railway (ER) will restart the Guava Special train from Baruipur to Sealdah from August 4. Announcing this on Monday, ER officials said the train will be re-introduced on demands from the orchard owners of Baruipur. 																																																		Prof Sudip Banerjee, heading the environmental science department of Calcutta University, has been appointed chairman of the West Bengal Pollution Control Board. Environment and information technology minister Manab Mukherjee handed over charge on Monday at the boards Salt Lake headquarters.																																																		A 36-year-old man and three of his relatives were arrested on Sunday from the Bowbazar area on charges of torturing his 18-year-old wife, whom he married a fortnight ago. According to police, Imroz Ahmed was picked up from his Phears Lane residence on the basis of a complaint lodged by his wife. Three others  Ahmeds brother-in-law Shamser Ansari and two sisters Shirin and Noorjahan  were also arrested.																																																		Police recovered the body of Bachcha Yadav, a truck-drivers help, in the Liluah police station area on Sunday. Police said Yadav had been shot from point-blank range. The body has been sent for post-mortem. 																																																		Police arrested an alleged kidnapper from the Sonarpur area, on the southern fringes of the city, on Sunday. The man was caught by the aunt of 13-year-old Soumen Nayek, when he was about to flee with the boy. 																																																		Members of the West Bengal Legislative Assembly paid homage to communist leader Hiren Mukherjee and singer Protima Bandyopadhyay on Monday. Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee said with Mukherjees death, the Left Front government has lost its guardian.																																																		The West Bengal Legislative Assembly on Monday passed the Bengal Engineering and Science University, Shibpur, Howrah, Bill, 2004. This will confer the status of a deemed university on the institution. Placing the bill, state higher education minister Satyasadhan Chakraborty said it would help the university function more efficiently as an institute. To the estate of the late Maharajkumari Jayasree Debi of Natore for gifting Rs 10 lakh to Ramakrishna Seva Pratishthan for a free bed and facilities for two patients
